{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nThe floor must key on VERIFIED delivery, never bare `closed` status — otherwise a force-closed or\nabandoned child would launder un-validated work past scrutiny, and a stale closed ticket can hard-\nblock the epic review (observed in practice).\n\n## What\n\nAdd a `delivered_now(child, epic, repo_root)` helper (in `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py`,\nreusing the `compute_validity(sig, child_state, 'completion-verifier')` validity-on-read check used INSIDE `_child_closure_findings` in `src/rebar/llm/completion.py` — note that fn is a DEFICIT detector (returns findings for children LACKING delivery), so we reuse its validity CALL applied to children whose status IS closed, NOT the fn itself) that returns True iff\nthe child is `closed` AND holds a completion-verifier attestation that is VALID on read\n(`compute_validity(..., \"completion-verifier\")` — so drift-stale / force-closed / unsigned all read\nfalse), OR child B is superseded by a SIBLING A (same parent; direction B superseded_by A) that is itself a live vehicle (delivered-now OR open/in_progress, not force-closed/abandoned) (read the\n`supersedes`/`duplicates` links via `src/rebar/__init__.py`; verify shared parent so work that left\nthe epic does not count as delivered). Recomputed each run. In-progress / abandoned / force-closed\nchildren return False -> stay in scope.\n\n## Scope\n\n- IN: the `delivered_now` predicate + its sibling-supersede check + validity-on-read reuse.\n- OUT: the Pass-3 wiring (separate story); the Pass-2 sub-call (separate story).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `delivered_now` is True for a closed child with a VALID completion attestation; False for force-closed, unsigned, drift-stale, in-progress, and abandoned children.\n- [ ] `delivered_now` treats B as delivered-elsewhere ONLY when a SIBLING A (same parent) supersedes B (direction: B superseded_by A) AND A is a live in-epic vehicle (delivered-now OR active open/in_progress); False when A is not a sibling or is itself force-closed/abandoned (closes the supersede-direction + replacement-not-done gap).\n- [ ] The predicate reuses the `compute_validity(..., 'completion-verifier')` validity-on-read call (NOT the deficit-detector `_child_closure_findings` itself), applied to closed children, and is recomputed per run (no persisted state).\n- [ ] Unit tests cover attested / force-closed / drift-stale / supersede-sibling / supersede-nonsibling / in-progress cases.\n\n## Supersede mechanism (concrete artifact)\n\nThe supersede relationship is the structured `supersedes` LINK RELATION (one of rebar's six link\nrelations) — an auditable, event-sourced graph edge in the ticket's deps, NOT a free-text note,\ntag, or naming convention. `delivered_now` reads it via `rebar.show`/`ticket_deps`: child B is\ndelivered-elsewhere iff a SIBLING A (same `parent_id`) has an `A supersedes B` edge (equivalently B\n`superseded_by` A) AND A is a live in-epic vehicle (delivered-now OR open/in_progress). Because the\nedge is a structured graph relation (not unsigned prose) AND the superseding sibling A stays in\nreview scope, this is NOT the unsigned/gameable suppression the Alternatives reject: no coverage is\nremoved (A is still reviewed), and the security/contract preserve-set (T5c/T10) is never dropped\nregardless of supersede — so a manipulated edge cannot launder a security finding.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria (mechanism)\n\n- [ ] The supersede signal is the structured `supersedes` link relation read from the child's deps (named artifact), not a note/tag/convention.\n- [ ] A test asserts the security/contract preserve-set is never dropped even when a supersede edge is present (no laundering).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria (reopen semantics)\n\n- [ ] A PARENT epic reopen does NOT un-deliver its closed children: ADR 0009 keys on each ticket's OWN `last_reopened_at`, so only a CHILD's own reopen invalidates that child's completion attestation. Closed children remain `delivered-now` across a parent reopen; a reopened child flips to not-delivered and its findings resurface."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782975901385720001,"uuid":"2b4b5b62-8878-4ca4-9ed1-4000a1fdfeae"}